docs.abstract: Companies are reconsidering where to put their factories as the trade war mounts, but few places can match China’s convenience and reliability.
docs.snippet: Companies are reconsidering where to put their factories as the trade war mounts, but few places can match China’s convenience and reliability.
docs.lead_paragraph: PHNOM PENH, Cambodia — The worsening trade war between the United States and China has intensified pressure on companies to leave China and set up factories in places like Cambodia, a verdant country of 16 million people with low wages and high hopes.

headline.main: Trump’s Tariffs May Hurt, but Quitting China Is Hard to Do
headline.print_headline: Quit China? It’s Not Going to Be Easy

docs.abstract: Robert Greenblatt is stepping away with NBC No. 1 in the ratings. His departure comes at a time of nearly unprecedented change at the highest ranks of the broadcast networks.
docs.snippet: Robert Greenblatt is stepping away with NBC No. 1 in the ratings. His departure comes at a time of nearly unprecedented change at the highest ranks of the broadcast networks.
docs.lead_paragraph: NBC’s entertainment chief, Robert Greenblatt, is stepping down from the company after almost eight years in charge, the latest change at the highest ranks of the major broadcast networks.

headline.main: NBC’s Entertainment Chief Leaves in Latest Broadcast TV Shakeup
headline.print_headline: NBC Executive Stepping Down In Latest Shift For Networks

docs.abstract: The entrepreneur Patrick Soon-Shiong says his company’s tests of zinc-based storage for solar and wind energy show the potential for large-scale use.

docs.lead_paragraph: Lithium-ion batteries have become essential for powering electric cars and storing energy generated by solar panels and wind turbines. But their drawbacks are also by now familiar: They use scarce minerals, are vulnerable to fires and explosions, and are pricey.

headline.main: Cheaper Battery Is Unveiled as a Step to a Carbon-Free Grid

docs.abstract: The classics can take you back in time — and are probably easier to recapture than you think.
docs.snippet: The classics can take you back in time — and are probably easier to recapture than you think.
docs.lead_paragraph: Video games hit their 60th birthday in October, if you start counting (as many do) with Tennis for Two, a rudimentary Pong ancestor cobbled together by the physicist William A. Higinbotham at Long Island’s Brookhaven National Laboratory. Games have evolved a lot since then, of course, becoming far more complicated and visual, as well as multiplayer.

headline.main: How to Find the Video Games of Your Youth
headline.print_headline: How to Go Back in Time to the Gaming Classics
